DURBAN - Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng was appointed Chancellor of the University of KwaZulu-Natal. The announcement was made by Reverend Dr Vukile Mehana, Chair of Council. Chief Justice Mogoeng is the fourth Chief Justice of the Republic of South Africa. He holds the B Juris and Bachelor of Laws (LLB) degrees from the Universities of Zululand and Natal respectively. He also holds a Master of Law (LLM) degree from the University of South Africa. The Chancellor is elected by Council and holds office for a period of four years. However, the Chancellorâ€™s tenure cannot exceed two consecutive terms in office. The Chief Justice is the third Chancellor and succeeds Dr Zweli Mkhize who served two four-year terms of office. Dr Frene Ginwala was the first Chancellor of the University, appointed in 2005. is the third Chancellor to hold the position at the University. According to the University Statute, the Chancellor is the official head of the University and presides over all congregations. He confers all degrees and awards, all diplomas and certificates at graduation. He will also perform functions assigned to him by the Council of the University. Mehana said the University was fortunate to have the Chief Justice to serve as Chancellor and they look forward to interacting with him in his role. He also thanked Dr Zweli Mkhize for his service to the University. In 2011, the Chief Justice was appointed Chief Justice and he also chairs the Judicial Service Commission (JSC), South African Judicial Education Institute (SAJEI) Council and National Efficiency Enhancement Committee (NEEC). He is also one of the Vice Presidents of Conference of Constitutional Jurisdictions of Africa (CCJA). Daily News